[{"data":1,"prerenderedAt":328},["ShallowReactive",2],{"header-locale:\u002Fen\u002Fjsweirdworld\u002F2019\u002F05\u002F15\u002Fjs-weird-world-02-name-value-pairs-objects\u002F":3,"page:\u002Fen\u002Fjsweirdworld\u002F2019\u002F05\u002F15\u002Fjs-weird-world-02-name-value-pairs-objects\u002F":4,"alt:\u002Fen\u002Fjsweirdworld\u002F2019\u002F05\u002F15\u002Fjs-weird-world-02-name-value-pairs-objects\u002F":3,"prev-next:\u002Fen\u002Fjsweirdworld\u002F2019\u002F05\u002F15\u002Fjs-weird-world-02-name-value-pairs-objects\u002F":304,"related:\u002Fen\u002Fjsweirdworld\u002F2019\u002F05\u002F15\u002Fjs-weird-world-02-name-value-pairs-objects\u002F":313},"\u002Fjsweirdworld\u002F20190515\u002F3276113437\u002F",{"id":5,"title":6,"abbrlink":7,"altUrl":3,"body":8,"category":287,"date":288,"description":289,"extension":290,"lang":291,"meta":292,"navigation":293,"path":294,"readingMinutes":295,"seo":296,"standalone":297,"stem":298,"tags":299,"tldr":301,"updated":288,"url":302,"__hash__":303},"content\u002Fen\u002FJsWeirdWorld\u002Fjs-weird-world-02-name-value-pairs-objects.md","[JS Weird World] No.2 Quick Concept Check: Name\u002FValue Pairs and Objects","1000087112",{"type":9,"value":10,"toc":282},"minimark",[11,16,24,27,30,63,66,69,85,92,109,113,118,121,124,156,166,169,175,178,256,259,265,269,278],[12,13,15],"h2",{"id":14},"namevalue-pairs","Name\u002FValue Pairs",[17,18,19],"p",{},[20,21],"img",{"alt":22,"src":23},"Name\u002Fvalue pairs","https:\u002F\u002Fi.imgur.com\u002FHPV57Gt.png",[17,25,26],{},"In short, a name only ever pairs with one single value. It's the same idea as a variable only holding one value at a time. That value can be a primitive value or an object, but either way, at any given moment a name maps to just one value.",[17,28,29],{},"Here's a quick example:",[31,32,37],"pre",{"className":33,"code":34,"language":35,"meta":36,"style":36},"language-js shiki shiki-themes github-dark-high-contrast","var a = 'hello';\n","js","",[38,39,40],"code",{"__ignoreMap":36},[41,42,45,49,53,56,60],"span",{"class":43,"line":44},"line",1,[41,46,48],{"class":47},"sWyjQ","var",[41,50,52],{"class":51},"sMAXC"," a ",[41,54,55],{"class":47},"=",[41,57,59],{"class":58},"sTRMh"," 'hello'",[41,61,62],{"class":51},";\n",[17,64,65],{},"This also ties into the \"execution context\". While a piece of code is running, a given name exists once, and it's paired with exactly one value — unless we go and change what's stored in it.",[17,67,68],{},"So say this is what's running right now:",[31,70,71],{"className":33,"code":34,"language":35,"meta":36,"style":36},[38,72,73],{"__ignoreMap":36},[41,74,75,77,79,81,83],{"class":43,"line":44},[41,76,48],{"class":47},[41,78,52],{"class":51},[41,80,55],{"class":47},[41,82,59],{"class":58},[41,84,62],{"class":51},[17,86,87,88,91],{},"And then we want to change the value to ",[38,89,90],{},"'hello2'",":",[31,93,95],{"className":33,"code":94,"language":35,"meta":36,"style":36},"a = 'hello2';\n",[38,96,97],{"__ignoreMap":36},[41,98,99,102,104,107],{"class":43,"line":44},[41,100,101],{"class":51},"a ",[41,103,55],{"class":47},[41,105,106],{"class":58}," 'hello2'",[41,108,62],{"class":51},[12,110,112],{"id":111},"objects","Objects",[17,114,115],{},[20,116],{"alt":112,"src":117},"https:\u002F\u002Fi.imgur.com\u002FGxj5WgC.png",[17,119,120],{},"The word \"object\" is deeply tied to JavaScript, and an object is itself a collection of name\u002Fvalue pairs.",[17,122,123],{},"For example:",[31,125,127],{"className":33,"code":126,"language":35,"meta":36,"style":36},"{\n name: 'Tom',\n}\n",[38,128,129,134,150],{"__ignoreMap":36},[41,130,131],{"class":43,"line":44},[41,132,133],{"class":51},"{\n",[41,135,137,141,144,147],{"class":43,"line":136},2,[41,138,140],{"class":139},"s_sBn"," name",[41,142,143],{"class":51},": ",[41,145,146],{"class":58},"'Tom'",[41,148,149],{"class":51},",\n",[41,151,153],{"class":43,"line":152},3,[41,154,155],{"class":51},"}\n",[17,157,158,161,162,165],{},[38,159,160],{},"name"," is the name, and ",[38,163,164],{},"Tom"," is the value.",[17,167,168],{},"Objects get really complicated in some other languages, but in JavaScript you don't need to overthink it. The course I'm following has a nice way of picturing it — an object basically looks like this:",[17,170,171],{},[20,172],{"alt":173,"src":174},"An object is just a name","https:\u002F\u002Fi.imgur.com\u002FR6q5QAb.png",[17,176,177],{},"So when I write something like this, you should be able to tell which parts are names and which are values:",[31,179,181],{"className":33,"code":180,"language":35,"meta":36,"style":36},"var a = {\n address: {\n  name:'tom',\n  ye: 3,\n  sweet: {\n   number: 100,\n  },\n },\n};\n",[38,182,183,194,199,209,221,227,238,244,250],{"__ignoreMap":36},[41,184,185,187,189,191],{"class":43,"line":44},[41,186,48],{"class":47},[41,188,52],{"class":51},[41,190,55],{"class":47},[41,192,193],{"class":51}," {\n",[41,195,196],{"class":43,"line":136},[41,197,198],{"class":51}," address: {\n",[41,200,201,204,207],{"class":43,"line":152},[41,202,203],{"class":51},"  name:",[41,205,206],{"class":58},"'tom'",[41,208,149],{"class":51},[41,210,212,215,219],{"class":43,"line":211},4,[41,213,214],{"class":51},"  ye: ",[41,216,218],{"class":217},"sCcAr","3",[41,220,149],{"class":51},[41,222,224],{"class":43,"line":223},5,[41,225,226],{"class":51},"  sweet: {\n",[41,228,230,233,236],{"class":43,"line":229},6,[41,231,232],{"class":51},"   number: ",[41,234,235],{"class":217},"100",[41,237,149],{"class":51},[41,239,241],{"class":43,"line":240},7,[41,242,243],{"class":51},"  },\n",[41,245,247],{"class":43,"line":246},8,[41,248,249],{"class":51}," },\n",[41,251,253],{"class":43,"line":252},9,[41,254,255],{"class":51},"};\n",[17,257,258],{},"Basically, don't make JavaScript more complicated than it is. Keep it simple, because JavaScript really is just this.",[260,261,262],"blockquote",{},[17,263,264],{},"It's just that simple.",[12,266,268],{"id":267},"image-source","Image Source",[17,270,271],{},[272,273,277],"a",{"href":274,"rel":275},"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.udemy.com\u002Fjavascriptjs\u002F",[276],"nofollow","JavaScript Deep Dive: Conquering the Weird Parts",[279,280,281],"style",{},"html pre.shiki code .sWyjQ, html code.shiki .sWyjQ{--shiki-default:#FF9492}html pre.shiki code .sMAXC, html code.shiki .sMAXC{--shiki-default:#F0F3F6}html pre.shiki code .sTRMh, html code.shiki .sTRMh{--shiki-default:#ADDCFF}html .default .shiki span {color: var(--shiki-default);background: var(--shiki-default-bg);font-style: var(--shiki-default-font-style);font-weight: var(--shiki-default-font-weight);text-decoration: var(--shiki-default-text-decoration);}html .shiki span {color: var(--shiki-default);background: var(--shiki-default-bg);font-style: var(--shiki-default-font-style);font-weight: var(--shiki-default-font-weight);text-decoration: var(--shiki-default-text-decoration);}html pre.shiki code .s_sBn, html code.shiki .s_sBn{--shiki-default:#FFB757}html pre.shiki code .sCcAr, html code.shiki .sCcAr{--shiki-default:#91CBFF}",{"title":36,"searchDepth":136,"depth":136,"links":283},[284,285,286],{"id":14,"depth":136,"text":15},{"id":111,"depth":136,"text":112},{"id":267,"depth":136,"text":268},"JsWeirdWorld","2019-05-15 10:54:35","A name only ever pairs with one single value — same idea as a variable only holding one value at a time. A name can be defined and reassigned many times, but at any given moment it maps to just one value. This post also covers how objects in JavaScript are really just collections of name\u002Fvalue pairs.","md","en",{},true,"\u002Fen\u002Fjsweirdworld\u002Fjs-weird-world-02-name-value-pairs-objects","2",{"title":6,"description":289},false,"en\u002FJsWeirdWorld\u002Fjs-weird-world-02-name-value-pairs-objects",[300,277],"JavaScript",null,"\u002Fen\u002Fjsweirdworld\u002F2019\u002F05\u002F15\u002Fjs-weird-world-02-name-value-pairs-objects\u002F","qlaKUa6NOt2XKiRT5xsei2VmSh4MgnnukkiSdm0nvOQ",{"newer":305,"older":309},{"url":306,"title":307,"date":308},"\u002Fen\u002Fjsweirdworld\u002F2019\u002F05\u002F15\u002Fjs-weird-world-03-global-environment-object\u002F","[JS Weird World] No.3 The Global Environment and the Global Object","2019-05-15 11:30:35",{"url":310,"title":311,"date":312},"\u002Fen\u002Fjsweirdworld\u002F2019\u002F05\u002F15\u002Fjs-weird-world-01-syntax-parser-execution-lexical-environment\u002F","The Weird Parts of JS (No.1): Syntax Parsers, Execution Contexts, and Lexical Environments","2019-05-15 09:54:35",[314,319,324],{"url":315,"title":316,"date":317,"readingMinutes":318},"\u002Fen\u002Fjsweirdworld\u002F2019\u002F05\u002F27\u002Fjs-weird-world-bonus-closures\u002F","[JS Weird World] Bonus: Closures, One More Time","2019-05-27 13:50:04","5",{"url":320,"title":321,"date":322,"readingMinutes":323},"\u002Fen\u002Fjsweirdworld\u002F2019\u002F05\u002F25\u002Fjs-weird-world-68-the-end-is-a-new-beginning\u002F","[JS Weird World] No.68 Wrapping Up the Weird Parts of JavaScript","2019-05-25 16:36:00","1",{"url":325,"title":326,"date":327,"readingMinutes":295},"\u002Fen\u002Fjsweirdworld\u002F2019\u002F05\u002F25\u002Fjs-weird-world-67-adding-jquery-support\u002F","[JS Weird World] No.67 Adding jQuery Support to Our Mini Framework","2019-05-25 16:19:00",1784011702945]